<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="40" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="21" pageNumber="40">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="21" pageNumber="40">
In the US, 
<taxonomicName genus="X." lsidName="X. glabratus" pageId="21" pageNumber="40" rank="species" species="glabratus">X. glabratus</taxonomicName>
was first detected in a survey trap near Port Wentworth, Georgia in 2002 (
<bibRefCitation author="Rabaglia, RJ" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="32" pageNumber="51" url="https://doi.org/10.1603/0013-8746(2006)99[1034:ROAXCC]2.0.CO;2" year="2006">Rabaglia et al. 2006</bibRefCitation>
). The ambrosia fungus vectored by this species is responsible for the death of 300 million bay trees (
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Lauraceae" genus="Persea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Persea" order="Laurales" pageId="21" pageNumber="40" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Persea</taxonomicName>
spp.) and other 
<taxonomicName family="Lauraceae" lsidName="" pageId="21" pageNumber="40" rank="family">Lauraceae</taxonomicName>
in the southeastern United States (
<bibRefCitation author="Hughes, MA" journalOrPublisher="Biological Invasions" pageId="31" pageNumber="50" pagination="2143 - 2157" title="No rest for the laurels: symbiotic invaders cause unprecedented damage to southern USA forests." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s10530-017-1427-z" volume="19" year="2017">Hughes et al. 2017</bibRefCitation>
). This species is distinguished by the dark color and the glabrous elytral disc and declivity with small granules in all interstriae decreasing in size toward apex.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
